item.title: Setting up R
item.description:
For class we will be using R, Rstudio and git. You can download and install each using the links below. However, you can instead use Rocker, a project built on top of Docker to manage your software installation. We’ve setup a container that will provide you with a working installation of R, and the Rstudio IDE, along with a lot of packages providing analysis tools and datasets we will use throughout the semester. You can read more about Rocker in this introduction

Downloads

If you would rather download and maintain your own software environment, download tools from these links:

  • R
  • Rstudio
  • git

Setting up Docker

These instructions are essentially following this document and have been tested mainly on Mac OSX. Install Docker according to the instructions for your system.

To check that docker works:

docker run hello-world

Setting up the course Docker image

We will be working from a docker image that extends the ropensci container provided by the Rocker project. It includes a a working installation of R, and the Rstudio IDE, along with many packages providing analysis tools and datasets we will use throughout the course. You can read more about Rocker in this introduction

This command will start an instance of this image.

docker run -d -p 8787:8787 -v ${PWD}:/home/rstudio --name ids hcorrada/idsdocker

This will take a while the first time you download it. After the download Rstudio Server will start (invisibly).

A couple of things to note:

  1. We will use Rstudio server through the web browser. The command -p 8787:8787 tells docker where you’re going to point your browser to run it.

  2. Docker runs on a virtual machine, we would like to be able to share files in your local machine with this virtual machine. The -v flag does that. Here ${PWD} corresponds to the current path in your local machine that will be mapped to the home directory in the docker virtual machine running rstudio (it is good practice to have a dedicated directory in your local machine where you do all work for this class mounted to the Docker container). You can read more about this here.

  3. It may also be possible that your personal computer does not, by default, allow the creation of virtual machines. The process of changing this setting is easy to do but will depend on your computer. The general idea is that you want to open your BIOS settings from start-up and change the virtualization setting there. As a general heuristic for doing so is here.

  4. We name the instance ids so we can refer to it in other commands later on.

Starting Rstudio

You will use Rstudio through your web browser. First, you need to know what is the address of your virtual machine. Users of Docker for Mac and Docker for Windows should be able to use the localhost address (http://127.0.0.1:8787). In other cases, you can find the address of the virtual machine by typing this in a terminal window:

docker-machine ip default

If, for example, this returned 192.168.59.103 then we can open Rstudio by pointing our web browser to http://192.168.59.103:8787 (remember we used port 8787 when we started the image).

Sign-in with username rstudio and password rstudio.

Try it out

The Rstudio IDE is divided into multiple panes. R is an interactive environment for data analysis. An interactive R session runs in the Console pane in Rstudio. You can enter R commands there:

> Sys.Date()
> data(cars)
> View(cars)
> plot(cars$dist, cars$speed)

The last command will make a scatter plot on the Plots pane.

Stopping the container

To stop and remove the running docker container, write:

docker stop ids
docker rm ids

Updating the image

When the image is updated to include new data or software you can use the following commands to pull the updated image and restart the docker container:

# pull updated version of image
docker pull hcorrada/idsdocker

# stop and remove the running container
docker stop ids
docker rm ids

# now restart the docker container with the updated image
docker run -d -p 8787:8787 -v ${PWD}:/home/rstudio --name ids hcorrada/idsdocker

Dockerfile

The Dockerfile defining the class image is hosted on Github here: https://github.com/hcorrada/idsDocker.

Permissions

Advanced Note: you don’t need to use sudo on Mac OSX. Linux users might want to add their user to the docker group to avoid having to use sudo. To do so, just run

sudo usermod -a -G docker <username>

You may need to login again to refresh your group membership.

Git

The course docker image also includes git a version control program we will use during the course. You will download all course materials using git and be able to update any changes I make along the way.

Version control will also be useful for reproducibility of your data analyses, also for sharing your analyses and contributing with collaborators.

To get started we will create a new Rstudio project by clicking on File->New Project...

and selecting Version Control to build the project from our course materials.

Select Git and enter the course repositories URL:

https://github.com/hcorrada/IntroDataSci.git

This will download all the course materials to your current directory.

One more thing: we are using the gh-pages branch to keep track of our materials. Go to the Git tab on Rstudio and on the branch dropdown (it should show master at first), select origin/gh-pages. Ok, now we’re done.

We will later see more information on how to use git.

Getting and AWS EC2 instance up and running

AWS (Amazon Web Services) provides Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) as a service that allows users to perform cloud computing (for a cost) without the cost of setting up the actual hardware necessary. For any of you familiar with MapReduce or Spark, EC2 instances are the way Amazon facilitates users interaction with those big data processing environments.

Without further ado, here are the instructions:

IMPORTANT; YOU WILL NEED TO DO THIS BEFORE ANYTHING ELSE:

  1. Go to http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/get-set-up-for-amazon-ec2.html#sign-up-for-aws
  2. Create an AWS account. In order to do this you will need to provide a phone number and a credit card. The phone number will be used to get a pin number and the credit card will receive a $1 charge that will be removed. While the accounts we will be setting up are free, Amazon charges for these products and will charge your account if you go over the 750 hour limit they provide. You can set up usage alarms at http://docs.aws.amazon.com/awsaccountbilling/latest/aboutv2/free-tier-alarms.html in order to avoid going over your limit and being charged.
  3. Create and IAM user and follow the instructions for creating a group for administrators.
  4. Create a key pair and be sure to keep your private key somewhere safe. Something you may need to do is change the permissions on the private key (for those of you using linux this would be chmod 400 name_of_the_private_key.pem).

ONCE YOU’VE CREATED A AN ACCOUNT AND AN IAM USER FOLLOW THESE INSTRUCTIONS:

  1. Sign into your AWS account and configure a t2.micro instance for launch. When choosing the AMI, note that these instructions cover Rocker setup for Amazon Linux AMI and Ubuntu Server 14.04 AMI. REQUIRED: While configuring your EC2 instance for launch, add these inbound rules for the security group you selected:
  • Type: “SSH”, Protocol: TCP, Port Range: 22, Source: my address (this will need to be updated when your local machine ip address changes)
  • Type: “SSH”: “custom TCP rule”, Protocol: TCP, port 8787, Source: my address (this will need to be updated when your local machine ip address changes)
  1. Connect to your EC2 instance. The EC2 Management Console provides the user name, host name, and SSH command after right clicking on an instance and choosing “Connect”. The easiest way to ssh into your EC2 instance is in docker. From docker run the command ssh -i "name_of_EC2_instance" ec2-user@ec2-54-209-79-237.compute-1.amazonaws.com

  2. If using an Amazon Linux AMI, install Docker as follows: http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/docker-basics.html#install_docker . If using an Ubuntu Server 14.04 AMI, install docker as follows starting with the “Install” heading (Half way down the page): https://docs.docker.com/engine/installation/linux/ubuntulinux/. IMPORTANT: the above OS refers to the OS of the AMI.

  3. Run:

$ docker run -d -p 8787:8787 -v ${PWD}:/home/rstudio --name ids hcorrada/idsdocker

To start Rstudio

  1. Determine your EC2 instance public ip address. This is accessible from the EC2 Management Console.
  2. On your local machine, point your browser to http://<ec2 instance public ip address>:8787
  3. Sign-in with username rstudio and password rstudio. Continue with Try it out

item.title: CMSC320 Resources
item.description:
R

  • R is an open-source environment for data analysis.
  • The RStudio IDE is highly recommended. The Revolution IDE is also very good, only Linux and Windows.
  • swirl is an interactive R (and general data analysis) tutorial
  • Data Camp has a nice short online course introducing R
  • R Task Views: The Machine Learning and Optimization Task Views list useful packages in R we may use.
  • R/Matlab references: A short R guide for Matlab users. A longer one.
  • R/Python references: A short R guide for Python users.

Docker

We will use Rocker, a project built on top of Docker to manage our software installation. This will provide you with a working installation of R, and the Rstudio IDE, along with a lot of packages providing analysis tools and datasets we will use throughout the semester. You can read more about Rocker in this introduction

Instructions on how to setup are found here

Other Resources

Rstudio has made some very nice cheatsheets for a number of workflows and tools we’ll look at this semester. You can find them here: https://www.rstudio.com/resources/cheatsheets/

You can find a nice list of free data science books here: http://www.wzchen.com/data-science-books/

Data Repositories

The Docker container you will install will contain access to a large number of data repositories. We will list additional ones here as we go along.

  • Kaggle: is a site hosting data competitions. It’s a great source of datasets, questions and tutorials.
  • Kaggle Datasets a new repository in Kaggle specifically for datasets, including code and scripts by users to get analyses on these datasets started.
  • data.gov: The U.S. goverment’s open data portal
  • Gapminder
  • Global Health Observatory: World Health Organization’s data repository.
  • UCI Machine Learning Repository: contains many datasets useful for testing and benchmarking learning algorithms.
  • StatLib: Statistical software and dataset portal maintained by CMU.
  • Another large list of repositories: http://www.inside-r.org/howto/finding-data-internet
  • Yet another list of public datasets: https://github.com/caesar0301/awesome-public-datasets
  • And yet another list of public datasets: http://blog.bigml.com/list-of-public-data-sources-fit-for-machine-learning/#national_governments
  • Airbnb data
  • NYC Taxi ride data
  • Resources for data journalism with R
  • Algorithms and datasets for computational social science and digital humanities

item.title: Logistics
item.description:
This page constiutes the official syllabus for this class.

Course Information

Introduction to Data Science
CMSC320 Fall 2016

  • Lecture Meeting Times
    Monday and Wednesday, 2:00pm-3:15pm, CSI 3117

  • Instructor:
    Héctor Corrada Bravo
    Center for Bioinformatics and Computational Biology
    Department of Computer Science
    hcorrada@umiacs.umd.edu
    Office: 3114F Biomolecular Sciences Building
    Phone Number: 301-405-2481
    Office Hours: Friday 1:00pm-2:00pm AVW 3223 and by appointment

  • Communication:

    • For course related questions, use Piazza as indicated below.
    • For any other communication (e.g., absences accomodations etc.) email me including [CMSC320] in the message subject.

  • TAs:

    • Virinchi Srinivas (Graduate)
      virinchimnm@gmail.com
      Office Hours: Mondays 10-12
    • Nolan Crane (Undergraduate)
      ncrane@umd.edu
      Office Hours: Tuesdays 2-3
    • Anant Dalela (Undergraduate)
      adalela@umd.edu
      Office Hours: Thursdays 2-3

We will use the class Piazza site https://piazza.com/class/isg1noi5k0765h for questions, dicussion and announcements. Assignments and grades for the class will be posted to the class ELMS site: https://myelms.umd.edu/courses/1199381 . In case of an extended emergency closure, announcements on policy and procedures will be posted to Piazza.

Textbook and Resources:

There is no required textbook, the lecture notes will serve as the primary material. However, we will be drawing heavily from these sources:

  • N. Zumel and J. Mount. Practical Data Science with R. Manning Publications Co. 2014.
  • G. James, D. Witten, T. Hastie and R. Tibshirani. Introduction to Statistical Learning with Applications in R. Springer 2013.. A free PDF of this book can be downloaded at their site.
  • EMC Education Services. Data Science & Big Analytics: Discovering, Analyzing, Visualizing and Presenting Data. Wiley, 2015

Additional readings will be posted in ELMS https://myelms.umd.edu/courses/1199381 .

Additional class resources are listed here

Course Description, Goals and Expectations

Data science encapsulates the interdisciplinary activities required to create data-centric products and applications that address specific scientific, socio-political or business questions. It has drawn tremendous attention from both academia and industry and is making deep inroads in industry, government, health and journalism.

This course focuses on (i) data management systems, (i) exploratory and statistical data analysis, (ii) data and information visualization, and (iv) the presentation and communication of analysis results. It will be centered around case studies and projects drawing extensively from applications.

Expected outcomes

1) Students will be able to create specific requirements for a data-centric application used to address a specific problem or question
2) Students will be able to identify and select appropriate tools: language, libraries and data resources, to meet specific requirements for a data-centric application
3) Students will be able to build and disseminate a data-centric application from a set of specific requirements using existing tools, libraries, data resources and publishing mechanisms.

Expectations for Students

  • There will be reading assignments. Students are expected to have read the material before class.
  • Students are expected to attend lectures. Active participation is expected. There will be graded work done in class.
  • Assignments are to be handed-in electronically or in class as instructed on their due date. Late assignments will not be accepted.
  • There will be graded work to be done in class. Students not in class that day, except for an excused absence, will not be able to complete that work outside class.
  • Students may discuss homeworks and projects in groups. However, each student must write and/or program solutions independently.
  • Posting project solutions in a public online location without express consent and permission from the instructor is a violation of academic integrity policy.
  • Cell phone usage is prohibited during lecture, laptop use will be allowed to the extent that students demonstrably use it to follow along an in-class analysis or demonstration.
  • You can earn full credit for class participation in three ways:
    (1) lecture participation, asking questions and answering your peers questions,
    (2) piazza participation, asking and answering questions on piazza,
    (3) regular attendance to office hours.
    To earn full credit you should aim to ask or answer a question at least once every two weeks on lecture or on piazza; or attend office hours at least once a month (this can include just going to my office hours to chat about computer science, data, science, software engineering, etc.).

Grading Procedures

  • Projects (35%)
  • In-class work (15%)
  • Written homework (20%)
  • Midterm exam (10%)
  • Final exam (15%)
  • Class participation (5%)

Tentative Course Schedule

  • Preliminaries: What is Data Science? Who is a Data Scientist? The scope of Data Science: the open data movement, science, business, government, education, sport, and more. Introduction to the R data analysis environment. Formulating data-centric answers to scientific, business and social questions. Best practices: organizing projects, managing collaborations and expectations.

  • Data Management Principles: Data scraping, tidying, cleaning and summarization. Basics of database systems and SQL. Exploratory Data Analysis. Exploration at scale: introduction to map reduce.

  • Computational and Statistical Data Analysis: From exploration to inference: statistical and probabilistic models. Linear modeling: regression and prediction. Introduction to Machine Learning: unsupervised methods, SVMs, tree-based methods

  • Data Mining: Regression and prediction at scale. Mining time series and data streams.

  • Communicating with data: Writing with and about data: communicating the result of a data analysis. Information visualization, visualizing for an audience. Putting it together: interactive data dissemination on the web (d3.js and related technologies).

Consult the class home page for an up-to-date course schedule.

University Policies and Resources

Policies relevant to Undergraduate Courses are found here: http://ugst.umd.edu/courserelatedpolicies.html. Topics that are addressed in these various policies include academic integrity, student and instructor conduct, accessibility and accommodations, attendance and excused absences, grades and appeals, copyright and intellectual property.

Course evaluations

Course evaluations are important and that the department and faculty take student feedback seriously. Students can go to http://www.courseevalum.umd.edu to complete their evaluations.

<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Measurements and data types</h1> <h4 class="author"><em>CMSC320</em></h4> <h4 class="date"><em>2016-09-09</em></h4>
</div>
<p>In this section we discuss different data types we will run across in different datasets. Lets use our arrest dataset for since weve become familiar with it by now.</p> <p>As a reminder, this is how you can obtain that dataset:</p> <pre class="r"><code>if (!file.exists("BPD_Arrests.csv")) { download.file("http://www.hcbravo.org/IntroDataSci/misc/BPD_Arrests.csv", destfile="BPD_Arrests.csv") } arrest_tab <- read.csv("BPD_Arrests.csv", stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
# remember there's a naming issue in this dataset we need to fix colnames(arrest_tab)[3:4] <- c("race", "sex")</code></pre> <div id="entities-and-attributes" class="section level2"> <h2>Entities and attributes</h2> <p>As a reminder, we are using the term <em>entities</em> to refer to the objects to which data in a dataset refers to. For instance, in our example dataset, each arrest is an <em>entity</em>. In a rectangular dataset, as weve seen before, this usually corresponds to rows in a table. We then say that a dataset contains <em>attributes</em> for each entity. For instance, attributes of each arrest would be the persons <em>age</em>, the type of offense, the location, etc. In a rectangular dataset, this corresponds to the columns in a table.</p> <p>This language of <em>entities</em> and <em>attributes</em> is commonly used in the database literature. In statistics you may see <em>experimental units</em> or <em>samples</em> for <em>entities</em> and <em>covariates</em> for <em>attributes</em>. In other instances <em>observations</em> for <em>entities</em> and <em>variables</em> for <em>attributes</em>. In Machine Learning you may see <em>example</em> for <em>entities</em> and <em>features</em> for <em>attributes</em>. For the most part, all of these are exchangable.</p> <p>This unit is concerned with the types of data we may encounter as <em>attributes</em> in data analyses.</p> </div> <div id="categorical-data" class="section level2"> <h2>Categorical data</h2> <p>A categorical attribute for a given entity can take only one of a finite set of examples. For example, the <code>sex</code> variable can only have value <code>M</code>, <code>F</code>, or `` (well talk about missing data later in the semester).</p> <pre class="r"><code>table(arrest_tab$sex)</code></pre> <pre><code>## ## F M ## 2 19431 85095</code></pre> <p>The result of a coin flip is categorical: <code>heads</code> or <code>tails</code>. The outcome of rolling an 8-sided die is categorical: <code>one</code>, <code>two</code>, , <code>eight</code>. Can you think of other examples?</p> <div id="factors-in-r" class="section level3"> <h3>Factors in R</h3> <p>We said that R is designed for data analysis. My favorite example of how that manifests itself is the <code>factor</code> datatype. If you look at your dataset now, <code>arrest_tab$sex</code> is a vector of strings:</p> <pre class="r"><code>class(arrest_tab$sex)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "character"</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code>summary(arrest_tab$sex)</code></pre> <pre><code>## Length Class Mode ## 104528 character character</code></pre> <p>However, as a measurement, or attribute, it should only take one of two values (or three depending on how you record missing, unknown or unspecified). So, in R, that categorical data type is called a <em>factor</em>. Notice what the <code>summary</code> function does after turning the <code>sex</code> attribute into a <em>factor</em>:</p> <pre class="r"><code>arrest_tab$sex <- factor(arrest_tab$sex) summary(arrest_tab$sex)</code></pre> <pre><code>## F M ## 2 19431 85095</code></pre> <p>This distinction shows up in many other places where functions have very different behavior when called on a vector of strings and when called on a factor (e.g., functions that make plots, or functions that learn statistical models).</p> <p>The possible values a <em>factor</em> can take are called <em>levels</em>:</p> <pre class="r"><code>levels(arrest_tab$sex)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "" "F" "M"</code></pre> <p>Exercise: you should transform the <code>race</code> attribute into a factor as well. How many levels does it have?</p> <p>Another note, when we used <code>read.csv</code> above to read our dataset from a text file, we used the argument <code>stringsAsFactors</code>. See if you can understand what that argument is used for.</p> </div> </div> <div id="discrete-numeric-data" class="section level2"> <h2>Discrete numeric data</h2> <p>These are attributes that can take specific values from elements of ordered, discrete (possibly infinite) sets. The most common set in this case would be the non-negative positive integers. This data is commonly the result of counting processes. In our example dataset, age, measured in years, is a discrete attribute.</p> <p>Frequently, we obtain datasets as the result of summarizing, or aggregating other underlying data. In our case, we could construct a new dataset containing the number of arrests per neighborhood:</p> <pre class="r"><code>library(dplyr)</code></pre> <pre><code>## ## Attaching package: 'dplyr'</code></pre> <pre><code>## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats': ## ## filter, lag</code></pre> <pre><code>## The following objects are masked from 'package:base': ## ## intersect, setdiff, setequal, union</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code>arrest_tab %>% group_by(neighborhood) %>% summarize(number_of_arrests=n()) %>% head()</code></pre> <pre><code>## # A tibble: 6 x 2 ## neighborhood number_of_arrests ## <chr> <int> ## 1 40727 ## 2 Abell 62 ## 3 Allendale 297 ## 4 Arcadia 78 ## 5 Arlington 694 ## 6 Armistead Gardens 153</code></pre> <p>In this new dataset, the <em>entities</em> are each neighborhood, the <code>number_of_arrests</code> attribute is a <em>discrete</em> attribute.</p> <p>Other examples: the number of students in a class is discrete, the number of friends for a specific Facebook user. Can you think of other datasets?</p> <p>Distinctions between categorical and discrete numerical data is that categorical data is not ordered and finite, discrete numeric data is (possibly) infite and ordered.</p> </div> <div id="continuous-numeric-data" class="section level2"> <h2>Continuous numeric data</h2> <p>These are attributes that can take any value in a continuous set. For example, a persons height, in say inches, can take any number (within the range of human heights). In our example dataset we do not have this type of data. However, here is another dataset we can use to look at this datatype:</p> <pre class="r"><code>data(cars) head(cars)</code></pre> <pre><code>## speed dist ## 1 4 2 ## 2 4 10 ## 3 7 4 ## 4 7 22 ## 5 8 16 ## 6 9 10</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code>plot(cars$speed, cars$dist, pch=19, xlab="speed (mph)", ylab="stopping distance (ft)")</code></pre> <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p> <p>The distinction between continuous and discrete is a bit tricky since measurements that have finite precision are, in a sense, discrete. Remember, however, that continuity is not a property of the specific dataset you have in hand, but rather of the process you are measuring. The number of arrests in a neighborhood cannot, in principle, be fractional, regardless of the precision at which we measure this. If we had the appropriate tool, we could measure a persons height with infinite precision. This distinction is very important when we build statistical models of datasets for analysis. For now, think of discrete data as the result of counting, and continuous data the result of some physical measurement.</p> </div> <div id="other-fun-examples" class="section level2"> <h2>Other fun examples</h2> <p>Consider a dataset of images like the super-famous <a href="https://www.kaggle.com/c/digit-recognizer">MNIST dataset of handwritten digits</a>. This dataset contains images of handwritten digits. So each image is an <em>entity</em>. Each image has a <em>label</em> attribute which states which of the digits 0,1,9 is represented by the image. What type of data is this (categorical, continuous numeric, or discrete numeric)?</p> <p>Now, each image is represented by grayscale values in a 28x28 grid. Thats 784 attributes, one for each square in the grid, containing a grayscale value. Now what type of data are these other 784 attributes?</p> </div> <div id="other-important-datatypes" class="section level2"> <h2>Other important datatypes</h2> <p>The three datatypes we saw above encompass a fairly large swath of data you will come across. Our arrest dataset contains other important datatypes that we will run across frequently:</p> <ul> <li>Datetime: Date and time of some event or observation (e.g., <code>arrestDate</code>, <code>arrestTime</code>)<br /> </li> <li>Geolocation: Latitude and Longitude of some event or observation (e.g., <code>Location.</code>)</li> </ul> </div> <div id="units" class="section level2"> <h2>Units</h2> <p>Something that we tend to forget but is <strong>extremely</strong> important for the modeling and interpretation of data is that attributes are for the most part <em>measurements</em> and that they have <em>units</em>. For example, age of a person can be measured in different units: <em>years</em>, <em>months</em>, etc. These can be converted to one another, but nonetheless in a given dataset, that <em>attribute</em> or measurement will be recorded in some specific units. Similar arguments go for distances and times, for example. In other cases, we may have unitless measurements (we will see later an example of this when we do <em>dimensionality reduction</em>). In these cases, it is worth thinking about <em>why</em> your measurements are unit-less.</p> <p>When performing analyses that try to summarize the effect of some measurement or attribute on another, units matter a lot! We will see the importance of this in our <em>regression</em> section. For now, make sure you make a mental note of units for each measurement you come across. This will force you to think about where and how your data was obtained, which will become very important when modeling and interpreting the results of these models.</p> </div>
</div>

<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Introduction to R</h1> <h4 class="author"><em>CMSC320</em></h4> <h4 class="date"><em>2016-08-31</em></h4>
</div>
<p>R is a computational environment for data analysis. It is designed around a <em>functional</em> language, as opposed to <em>procedural</em> languages like Java or C, that has desirable properties for the type of operations and workflows that are frequently performed in the course of analyzing datasets. In this exercise we will start learning some of those desirable properties while performing an analysis of a real dataset.</p> <div id="some-history" class="section level2"> <h2>Some history</h2> <p>R is an offspring of S, a language created in AT&T Labs by John Chambers (now at Stanford) and others in 1976 with the goal of creating an environment for statistical computing and data analysis. The standard for the language in current use was settled in 1998. That same year, S won the ACM Software System award, awarded to software systems that have a lasting influence, reflected in contributions to concepts, in commercial acceptance, or both.</p> <p>In 1991, Robert Gentleman and Ross Ihaka created R to provide an open source implementation of the S language and environment. They also redesigned the language to enforce lexical scoping rules. It has been maintained by the R core group since 1997, and in 2015 an R consortium, including Microsoft, Google, and others, was created.</p> <p>Along with Python it is one of the most popular environments for data analysis (e.g., figure below from <a href="http://www.kdnuggets.com/2016/06/r-python-top-analytics-data-mining-data-science-software.html">KDNuggets 2016 software survey</a>) <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt /><!-- --></p> <p>We use it for this class because we find that besides it being a state-of-the-art data analysis environment, it provides a clean end-to-end platform for teaching material across the data management-modeling-communication spectrum that we study in class.</p> </div> <div id="availability-and-eco-system" class="section level2"> <h2>Availability and eco-system</h2> <p>R is freely available at <a href="http://www.r-project.org/" class="uri">http://www.r-project.org/</a>. A number of good IDEs are available for its use:</p> <ul> <li><a href="http://rstudio.org">Rstudio</a><br /> </li> <li><a href="http://www.revolutionanalytics.com/get-revolution-r">Revolution R</a></li> </ul> <p>You can also find bindings for commonly used editors and IDEs, like <a href="http://ess.r-project.org/">emacs</a> and <a href="http://www.walware.de/goto/statet">eclipse</a>.</p> <p>Resources for learning and reading about R are listed in our <a href="http://www.hcbravo.org/IntroDataScience/resources/">course page</a>. Of note are the <a href="http://swirlstats.com/">swirl project</a> and DataCamps [introduction to R] course.</p> <p>One of the biggest strengths of the R ecosystem is the variety and quality of packages for data analysis available. R uses a package system (like Python and Ruby for instance). Packages are divided into two classes: <strong>base</strong> which are packages installed when R is installed, includes packages for basic statistics, computing with probability distributions, plotting and graphics, matrix manipulations and other), all other packages are available in <a href="http://cran.r-project.org">CRAN</a>. We will be using a fair number of these packages through the course of the semester.</p> </div> <div id="how-to-think-about-r" class="section level2"> <h2>How to think about R</h2> <p>As we wrote previously, R is an environment for data analysis, centered around a <em>functional</em> language designed for common operations in data analysis. When we say that R is a <em>functional</em> language, at its most basic definition, means that we treat <em>functions</em> as values. For instance, we can assign <em>functions</em> to variables, or pass <em>functions</em> as arguments to other <em>functions</em>. Well see examples of that later on. If you are familiar with Ruby or Python, while they are not functional languages, they do have some idioms of functional languages that may be familiar: <a href="http://www.sitepoint.com/functional-programming-techniques-with-ruby-part-i/" class="uri">http://www.sitepoint.com/functional-programming-techniques-with-ruby-part-i/</a>, <a href="https://docs.python.org/2/howto/functional.html" class="uri">https://docs.python.org/2/howto/functional.html</a>.</p> <p>With that in mind, its useful to think of R as supporting three ways of thinking how to organize computation:</p> <ol style="list-style-type: decimal"> <li>Functions and lists, in the <em>functional</em> language sense described above,<br /> </li> <li>Numerical computation, operations over vectors, matrices and similar mathematical structures,<br /> </li> <li>Operations over <em>data tables</em> (think spreadsheets in Excel, or individual tables in a database). We will start our introduction to R here.</li> </ol> </div> <div id="literate-programming" class="section level2"> <h2>Literate Programming</h2> <p>One last note before we get started. R has great support for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Literate_programming">literate programming</a>, where source code that contains both code, the result of evaluating that code, and text explaining that code co-exist in a single document. This is extremely valuable in data analysis, as many choices made by data analysts are worth explaning in text, and interpretation of the results of analyses can co-exist with the computations used in that analysis. This document you are reading contains both text and code. In class, we will use <a href="http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com/">Rmarkdown</a> for this purpose.</p> </div> <div id="a-simple-data-analysis-to-get-us-going" class="section level2"> <h2>A simple data analysis to get us going</h2> <p>Im going to do a very simple analysis of Baltimore crime to show off R. Well use data downloaded from Baltimore Citys awesome open data site (this was downloaded a couple of years ago so if you download now, you will get different results).</p> <p>The repository for this particular data is here. <a href="https://data.baltimorecity.gov/Crime/BPD-Arrests/3i3v-ibrt" class="uri">https://data.baltimorecity.gov/Crime/BPD-Arrests/3i3v-ibrt</a></p> <p>First, make sure you can get Rstudio running. See <a href="http://www.hcbravo.org/IntroDataSci/homeworks/rocker/">this page</a> for instructions.</p> <p>We recommend that you use Rstudio for this class. Once open you will see Rstudio is organized into multiple panes. You will have a console into which you can write and execute commands directly. You will also have an editor pane where you can edit R source code. R scripts (only containing commands) are stored in <code>.R</code> files, Rmarkdown files (containing both commands and text) are stored in <code>.Rmd</code> files. You can follow along by writing commands shown here either in an <code>R</code>, or <code>Rmd</code> file and executing commands from the editor pane.</p> <div id="getting-data" class="section level3"> <h3>Getting data</h3> <p>Weve prepared the data previously into a comma-separated value file (<code>.csv</code> file). In this format, each line contains <em>attribute</em> values (separated by commas) for one <em>entity</em> in our dataset. Which we can download and load into our R environment.</p> <pre class="r"><code>if (!file.exists("BPD_Arrests.csv")) { download.file("http://www.hcbravo.org/IntroDataSci/misc/BPD_Arrests.csv", destfile="BPD_Arrests.csv") }</code></pre> <p>The <code>read.csv</code> command is part of base R and allows you to read a dataset stored in a csv file. This function is extremely versatile, and you can read more about it by using the standard help system in R: <code>?read.csv</code>. Now, the result of running calling this function is the data itself, so, by running the function in the console, the result of the function is printed.</p> </div> <div id="variables-and-value" class="section level3"> <h3>Variables and Value</h3> <p>To make use of this dataset we want to assign the result of calling <code>read.csv</code> (i.e., the dataset) to a variable:</p> <pre class="r"><code>arrest_tab <- read.csv("BPD_Arrests.csv", stringsAsFactors=FALSE)</code></pre> <p>Now we can ask what <em>type</em> of value is stored in the <code>arrest_tab</code> variable:</p> <pre class="r"><code>class(arrest_tab)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "data.frame"</code></pre> <p>The <code>data.frame</code> is a workhorse data structure in R. It encapsulates the idea of <em>entities</em> (in rows) and <em>attribute values</em> (in columns). We can ask other features of this dataset:</p> <pre class="r"><code># This is a comment in R, by the way
# How many rows (entities) does this dataset contain? nrow(arrest_tab)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 104528</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># How many columns (attributes)? ncol(arrest_tab)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 15</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># What are the names of those columns? colnames(arrest_tab)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "arrest" "age" "sex" ## [4] "race" "arrestDate" "arrestTime" ## [7] "arrestLocation" "incidentOffense" "incidentLocation" ## [10] "charge" "chargeDescription" "district" ## [13] "post" "neighborhood" "Location.1"</code></pre> <p>Now, in Rstudio you can view the data frame using <code>View(arrest_tab)</code>, which can be very useful.</p> </div> <div id="indexing" class="section level3"> <h3>Indexing</h3> <p>Now a basic operation in data analysis is selecting subsets of a dataset. For that we can use a few alternative options for <em>indexing</em> into datasets.</p> <pre class="r"><code># to obtain the value in the first row, fifth column: arrest_tab[1,5]</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "01/01/2011"</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># note that indexing in R is 1-based, not 0-based, so the first row is indexed by 1
# now we want to do a bit more, so let's say we want the value in the fifth column of our dataset for the first 10 rows. For that we can use slice notation: arrest_tab[1:10,5]</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "01/01/2011" "01/01/2011" "01/01/2011" "01/01/2011" "01/01/2011" ## [6] "01/01/2011" "01/01/2011" "01/01/2011" "01/01/2011" "01/01/2011"</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># similarly, to obtain the value in the first five columns of the first row arrest_tab[1,1:5]</code></pre> <pre><code>## arrest age sex race arrestDate ## 1 11126858 23 B M 01/01/2011</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># what is the class of the value when we subset a single column? class(arrest_tab[1:10,5])</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "character"</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># what is the class of the value when we subset a single row? class(arrest_tab[1,1:5])</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "data.frame"</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># what do we get with this indexing? arrest_tab[1:10,1:5]</code></pre> <pre><code>## arrest age sex race arrestDate ## 1 11126858 23 B M 01/01/2011 ## 2 11127013 37 B M 01/01/2011 ## 3 11126887 46 B M 01/01/2011 ## 4 11126873 50 B M 01/01/2011 ## 5 11126968 33 B M 01/01/2011 ## 6 11127041 41 B M 01/01/2011 ## 7 11126932 29 B M 01/01/2011 ## 8 11126940 20 W M 01/01/2011 ## 9 11127051 24 B M 01/01/2011 ## 10 11127018 53 B M 01/01/2011</code></pre> <p>We can index any set of rows or columns by constructing <em>vectors</em> of integers. In fact, the slice notation <code>:</code> is essentially doing that for a sequence of consecutive indices. You should think of vectors as lists of values with the same class.</p> <p>If we want non-consecutive indices we have other options (e.g., the <code>c</code> function, for concatenate)</p> <pre class="r"><code># non-consecutive indices using c arrest_tab[c(2,4,7,10), 1:5]</code></pre> <pre><code>## arrest age sex race arrestDate ## 2 11127013 37 B M 01/01/2011 ## 4 11126873 50 B M 01/01/2011 ## 7 11126932 29 B M 01/01/2011 ## 10 11127018 53 B M 01/01/2011</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># here's a fun one, when we call columns for a subset of rows arrest_tab[c(2,4,7,10), ]</code></pre> <pre><code>## arrest age sex race arrestDate arrestTime arrestLocation ## 1 23 B M ## 2 37 B M ## 3 46 B M ## 4 50 B M ## 5 33 B M ## 6 41 B M ## 7 29 B M ## 8 20 W M ## 9 24 B M ## 10 53 B M</code></pre> <p>If we wanted a single named column from a data frame theres a special operator <code>$</code> to index:</p> <pre class="r"><code># first ten values of the age column arrest_tab$age[1:10]</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 23 37 46 50 33 41 29 20 24 53</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># EXERCISE # try using three different ways of selecting rows 20 to 30 # of the "sex" column</code></pre> <p>In addition to integer indices or names, we can use vectors of logical values for indexing.</p> <pre class="r"><code># rows 2,4,7 and 10 using logical indices arrest_tab[c(FALSE,TRUE,FALSE,TRUE,FALSE,FALSE,TRUE,FALSE,FALSE,TRUE,rep(FALSE,nrow(arrest_tab)-10)),]</code></pre> <pre><code>## arrest age sex race arrestDate arrestTime arrestLocation ## 9 ## 11 Central Park Heights (39.3436773374, -76.6727297618)</code></pre> <p>The last example shows one of the most common gotchas in R. Indices are recycled. For instance if selecting rows, if you pass a logical vector thats shorter than the number of rows in the data frame, the vector will be recycled as many times as necessary to match the number of rows in the dataset. Now, why is this useful, because a pithy index vector can let you select easily. Why is this bad, because errors in code can go easily unnoticed. So in this case, the price of ease of use is paid by the programmer by having to think a lot more carefully about their code (this is a theme in R programming)</p> <p>The utility of logical indexing is that now we can select rows based on a property of its values for a given column</p> <pre class="r"><code># select rows for entities younger than 21 years old head(arrest_tab[arrest_tab$age < 21, ])</code></pre> <pre><code>## arrest age sex race arrestDate arrestTime arrestLocation ## 8 11126940 20 W M 01/01/2011 00:05 5200 Moravia Rd ## 30 11126942 20 B M 01/01/2011 01:22 1900 Ashburton Ave ## 39 11126941 20 W M 01/01/2011 02:00 300 S Bentalou St ## 41 11126955 20 B M 01/01/2011 02:20 900 Myrtle Ave ## 42 11127139 19 W M 01/01/2011 02:22 4500 Erdman Ave ## 43 11127003 20 B F 01/01/2011 02:49 2400 Brentwood St ## incidentOffense incidentLocation charge ## 8 Unknown Offense 1 5200 ## 30 79-Other 2200 Ashburton St 1 5285 ## 39 4C-Agg. # select entities (arrests) occuring in Mount Washington, # a specific neighborhood in Baltimore head(arrest_tab[arrest_tab$neighborhood == "Mount Washington",])</code></pre> <pre><code>## arrest age sex race arrestDate arrestTime arrestLocation ## 2334 11137346 30 B M 01/20/2011 20:00 2900 W Northern Park ## 2340 11137358 30 B M 01/20/2011 20:15 2900 W Northern Park ## 3060 11140601 26 B M 01/26/2011 20:00 5700 Pimlico Rd ## 6496 NA 22 B M 02/19/2011 23:45 0 South St ## 17993 11213825 24 B F 05/09/2011 18:30 5800 Key Ave ## 20002 11222982 21 B M 05/21/2011 01:00 5700 W Merville Ave ## incidentOffense incidentLocation charge ## 2334 24-Towed Vehicle 5600 Merville Av ## 2340 24-Towed Vehicle 5600 Merville Av 1 0573 ## 3060 87-Narcotics 5700 Pimlico Rd ## 6496 Unknown Offense ## 17993 6B-Larceny- Purse Snatch 5800 Key Av 3 4025 ## 20002 24-Towed Vehicle 5700 Merville Av ## chargeDescription district post ## 2334 Unknown Charge NORTHERN 535 ## 2340 Cds: Possession-Marihuana || Cds Violation NORTHERN 535 ## 3060 Unknown Charge NORTHERN 535 ## 6496 Unknown Charge NORTHERN 535 ## 17993 Mal Dest Prop/Valu - $500 || 2Nd Degree Assault NORTHWESTERN 635 ## 20002 Unknown Charge NORTHERN 535 ## neighborhood Location.1 ## 2334 Mount Washington (39.3563987461, -76.6763954468) ## 2340 Mount Washington (39.3563987461, -76.6763954468) ## 3060 Mount Washington (39.3597311724, -76.6715583289) ## 6496 Mount Washington (39.3608880210, -76.6641650850) ## 17993 Mount Washington (39.3585990772, -76.6792007267) ## 20002 Mount Washington (39.3587518907, -76.6759724031)</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># how about arrests where subjects are under 21 in Mount Washington? # use a logical `and` operator indices <- arrest_tab$age < 21 & arrest_tab$neighborhood == "Mount Washington"</code></pre> </div> </div> <div id="exploration" class="section level2"> <h2>Exploration</h2> <p>R has built-in functions that help easily obtain summary information about datasets. For instance:</p> <pre class="r"><code>summary(arrest_tab$sex)</code></pre> <pre><code>## A B H I U W ## 2 242 87268 1 218 1749 15048</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code>summary(arrest_tab$race)</code></pre> <pre><code>## F M ## 2 19431 85095</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># well that seems problematic # let's rename columns to correct that colnames(arrest_tab)[3:4] <- c("race", "sex")</code></pre> <p>We can also ask other useful type of summaries</p> <pre class="r"><code># What is the average age in arrests? mean(arrest_tab$age)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 33.19639</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># Median age? median(arrest_tab$age)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 30</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># what types of offenses are there summary(arrest_tab$incidentOffense)</code></pre> <pre><code>## Unknown Offense 87-Narcotics ## 38649 24744 ## 4E-Common Assault 87O-Narcotics (Outside) ## 6739 6515 ## 97-Search & Seizure 79-Other ## 3670 3461 ## 24-Towed Vehicle 6C-Larceny- Shoplifting ## 2994 1849 ## 4C-Agg. Median Mean 3rd Qu. Max. ## 0.0 23.0 30.0 33.2 43.0 87.0</code></pre> <p>Combining this type of summary with our indexing strategies we learned previously we can ask more specific questions</p> <pre class="r"><code># What is the average age for arrests in Mount Washington? mount_washington_index <- arrest_tab$neighborhood == "Mount Washington"
mean(arrest_tab$age[mount_washington_index])</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 31.10345</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># How about the number of arrests in Mount Washington _stratified_ by race and sex? table(arrest_tab$race[mount_washington_index], arrest_tab$sex[mount_washington_index])</code></pre> <pre><code>## ## F M ## 0 0 0 ## A 0 0 0 ## B 0 4 14 ## H 0 0 0 ## I 0 0 0 ## U 0 0 0 ## W 0 2 9</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code># how about a graphical summary of arrest ages in Mount Washington? # we'll use a boxplot boxplot(arrest_tab$age[mount_washington_index])</code></pre> <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p> <pre class="r"><code># can we do the same stratified by age? boxplot(arrest_tab$age[mount_washington_index]~arrest_tab$sex[mount_washington_index])</code></pre> <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p> <p>This used a very useful notation in R: the tilde, <code>~</code> which we will encounter in a few different places. One way of thinking about that abstractly is, do something with this attribute, as a function (or depending on, stratified by, conditioned on) this other attribute. For instance, plot <code>age</code> as a function of sex in our example.</p> <p>Lets write code thats a little cleaner for that last plot, and lets also make the plot a bit more useful by adding a title and axis labels:</p> <pre class="r"><code>mount_washington_tab <- arrest_tab[mount_washington_index,] boxplot(mount_washington_tab$age~mount_washington_tab$sex, main="Mt. Washington", xlab="Sex", ylab="Arrest Age")</code></pre> <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p> <p>Heres one more useful plot:</p> <pre class="r"><code>barplot(table(mount_washington_tab$race), xlab="Number of Arrests", ylab="Race")</code></pre> <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p> <div id="functions-and-conditionals" class="section level3"> <h3>Functions (and conditionals)</h3> <p>Now suppose we wanted to do a similar analysis for other neighborhoods. In that case we should encapsulate the summaries and plots we want to do in a function:</p> <pre class="r"><code>analyze_neighborhood <- function(neighborhood) { neighborhood_index <- arrest_tab$neighborhood == neighborhood neighborhood_tab <- arrest_tab[neighborhood_index,]
# actually, we only want to make the plots for neighborhoods where there are more arrests for whites than blacks, let's use a conditional expression if (sum(neighborhood_tab$race == "W") > sum(neighborhood_tab$race == "B")) {
boxplot(neighborhood_tab$age~neighborhood_tab$sex, main = neighborhood, xlab = "Sex", ylab="Arrest Age")
barplot(table(neighborhood_tab$race), main = neighborhood, xlab = "Race", ylab="Number of Arrests") } }</code></pre> <p>Now we can use that function to make our plots for specific neighborhoods</p> <pre class="r"><code>analyze_neighborhood("Mount Washington") analyze_neighborhood("Hampden")</code></pre> <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p> </div> </div> <div id="loops" class="section level2"> <h2>Loops</h2> <p>Finally, we can use a for loop to make these plots for all neighborhoods in the dataset and save them to a pdf file</p> <pre class="r"><code>neighborhoods <- unique(arrest_tab$neighborhood)
# open a pdf file and save all plots to that file from # this point until file is closed pdf("neighborhood_analysis.pdf", width=6, height=6) for (neighborhood in neighborhoods) { analyze_neighborhood(neighborhood) } # close the pdf file (plots will now be displayed in Rstudio again) dev.off()</code></pre> <pre><code>## quartz_off_screen ## 2</code></pre> </div> <div id="next-up" class="section level2"> <h2>Next up</h2> <p>On the intricacies of vectorized operations and loops. Matrices and other numerical computing facilities.</p> </div>

<div class="fluid-row" id="header">
<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Introduction to R (part 2)</h1> <h4 class="author"><em>CMSC320</em></h4> <h4 class="date"><em>2016-09-04</em></h4>
</div>
<div id="getting-started" class="section level2"> <h2>Getting started</h2> <p>Lets load the same data we used in the previous lab (look there for instructions on how to download).</p> <pre class="r"><code>arrest_tab <- read.csv("BPD_Arrests.csv", stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
# remember there's a naming issue in this dataset we need to fix colnames(arrest_tab)[3:4] <- c("race", "sex")</code></pre> </div> <div id="a-note-on-data-types" class="section level2"> <h2>A note on data types</h2> <p>This dataset contains data of types commonly found in data analyses</p> <ul> <li>Numeric (continuous): A numeric measurement (e.g., height)<br /> </li> <li>Numeric (discrete): Usually obtained from counting, think only integers (e.g., <code>age</code> which is measured in years)<br /> </li> <li>Categorical: One of a possible set of values (e.g., <code>sex</code>)<br /> </li> <li>Datetime: Date and time of some event or observation (e.g., <code>arrestDate</code>, <code>arrestTime</code>)<br /> </li> <li>geolocation: Latitude and Longitude of some event or observation (e.g., <code>Location.</code>)</li> </ul> <p>The distinction between continuous and discrete is a bit tricky since measurements that have finite precision must be discrete. So, the difference really comes up when we build statistical models of datasets for analysis. For now, think of discrete data as the result of counting, and continuous data the result of some physical measurement.</p> <p>We said that R is designed for data analysis. My favorite example of how that manifests itself is the <code>factor</code> datatype. If you look at your dataset now, <code>arrest_tab$sex</code> is a vector of strings:</p> <pre class="r"><code>class(arrest_tab$sex)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "character"</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code>summary(arrest_tab$sex)</code></pre> <pre><code>## Length Class Mode ## 104528 character character</code></pre> <p>However, as a measurement, or attribute, it should only take one of two values (or three depending on how you record missing, unknown or unspecified). So, in R, that categorical data type is called a <em>factor</em>. Notice what the <code>summary</code> function does after turning the <code>sex</code> attribute into a <em>factor</em>:</p> <pre class="r"><code>arrest_tab$sex <- factor(arrest_tab$sex) summary(arrest_tab$sex)</code></pre> <pre><code>## F M ## 2 19431 85095</code></pre> <p>This distinction shows up in many other places where functions have very different behavior when called on a vector of strings and when called on a factor (e.g., functions that make plots, or functions that learn statistical models).</p> <p>One last note, the possible values a <em>factor</em> can take are called <em>levels</em>:</p> <pre class="r"><code>levels(arrest_tab$sex)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "" "F" "M"</code></pre> <p>Exercise: you should transform the <code>race</code> attribute into a factor as well. How many levels does it have?</p> </div> <div id="thinking-in-vectors" class="section level2"> <h2>Thinking in vectors</h2> <p>In data analysis the <em>vector</em> is probably the most fundamental data type (other than basic numbers, strings, etc.). Why? Consider getting data about one attribute, say height, for a group of people. What do you get, an array of numbers, all in the same unit (say feet, inches or centimeters). How about their name? Then you get an array of strings. Abstractly, we think of vectors as arrays of values, all of the same <em>class</em> or datatype.</p> <p>In our dataset, each column, corresponding to an attribute, is a vector:</p> <pre class="r"><code># the 'str' function gives a bit more low-level information about objects str(arrest_tab$Location)</code></pre> <pre><code>## chr [1:104528] "" "(39.2814026274, -76.6483635135)" ...</code></pre> <p>R (and other data analysis languages) are designed to operate on vectors easily. For example, frequently we want to do some kind of transformation to a data attribute, say record age in months rather than years. Then we would perform the <strong>same operation</strong> for every value in the corresponding vector:</p> <pre class="r"><code>age_in_months <- arrest_tab$age * 12</code></pre> <p>In a language that doesnt support this type of vectorized operation, you would use a loop, or similar construct, to perform this operation.</p> <p>Another type of transformation frequently done is to combine attributes into a single attribute. Suppose we wanted to combine the <code>arrestLocation</code> and <code>neighborhood</code> attributes into an <code>address</code> attribute:</p> <pre class="r"><code># remember you can always find out what a function does by using ?paste head(paste(arrest_tab$arrestLocation, arrest_tab$neighborhood, sep=", "))</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] ", " ## [2] "2000 Wilkens Ave, Carrollton Ridge" ## [3] "2800 Mayfield Ave, Belair-Edison" ## [4] "2100 Ashburton St, Panway/Braddish Avenue" ## [5] "4000 Wilsby Ave, Pen Lucy" ## [6] "2900 Spellman Rd, Cherry Hill"</code></pre> <p>Here the <code>paste</code> function concatenates strings element-wise: the first string in <code>arrestLocation</code> is concatenated with the first string in <code>neighborhood</code>, etc.</p> <p>Arithmetic operations have the same element-wise operation:</p> <pre class="r"><code># add first 10 odd numbers to first 10 even numbers seq(1, 20, by=2) + seq(2, 20, by=2)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 3 7 11 15 19 23 27 31 35 39</code></pre> </div> <div id="functions-as-values-and-vectorized-operations" class="section level2"> <h2>Functions as values and vectorized operations</h2> <p>Now here is where we see the value of using a <em>functional language</em> for data analysis. In data analysis, when you want to perform some operation on a vector of values, a very common coding pattern that arises is to (a) define a function that takes one value, and returns one value, and then (b) <em>apply</em> this function to every entry in the vector.</p> <p>Heres one example: suppose we want to create a new attribute that specifies if the person arrested is under-age (younger that 18). We can (a) define a function that takes an age, and the uses a conditional (if statement) to return youth or adult depending on the age.</p> <pre class="r"><code>make_age_categorical <- function(age) { if (age < 18) { "youth" } else { "adult" } }</code></pre> <p>A couple of notes about functions in R based on this example. This function has a single <em>expression</em>, the <code>if</code> statement. The <em>result</em> of evaluating this expression is either <code>"youth"</code> or <code>"adult"</code>. So the <em>value</em> of the <code>if</code> statement is going to be a string. Notice also, that there is no <code>return</code> statement in this function. The result of calling a function is the <em>value</em> of the last <em>expression</em> in the function definition.</p> <p>Now that we have a function in place, we can <em>apply</em> this function to the <code>age</code> attribute in our dataset to get our new categorical age attribute:</p> <pre class="r"><code>categorical_age <- sapply(arrest_tab$age, make_age_categorical) str(categorical_age)</code></pre> <pre><code>## chr [1:104528] "adult" "adult" "adult" "adult" "adult" ...</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code>table(categorical_age)</code></pre> <pre><code>## categorical_age ## adult youth ## 104065 463</code></pre> <p>Every functional language has a function like <code>sapply</code>: it takes a vector (or list) and a function and applies the function to each entry in the vector.</p> <p>Now, as you may imagine, the type of transformation we did here is a pattern that is used very frequently in data analysis. R has operations (the <code>ifelse</code> function) to make this easier:</p> <pre class="r"><code># ifelse takes a vector of logical values and returns one of two options based on the result
categorical_age <- ifelse(arrest_tab$age < 18, "youth", "adult") str(categorical_age)</code></pre> <pre><code>## chr [1:104528] "adult" "adult" "adult" "adult" "adult" ...</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code>table(categorical_age)</code></pre> <pre><code>## categorical_age ## adult youth ## 104065 463</code></pre> <p>This is again a vectorized operation. As we progress through the semester we will see value of thinking with vectors, vectorized operations and applying functions as we do data analysis.</p> </div> <div id="side-effects-and-functional-languages" class="section level2"> <h2>Side-effects and functional languages</h2> <p>Another fundamental design decision in R, as a functional language, is that functions <em>should</em> have no <em>side-effects</em>. Lets look at a simple example</p> <pre class="r"><code>x <- 2 f <- function(x) { x <- 6 x } f(x)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 6</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code>x</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 2</code></pre> <p>In this case, the assignment <code>x <- 6</code> inside function <code>f</code> has no effect on the value of variable <code>x</code> outside function <code>f</code>. In that case, assignment <code>x <- 6</code> has no side-effects.</p> <p>This is a desirable property for data analysis because it is much easier to reason about programs when functions have no <em>side-effects</em>. On the other hand, this can have a detrimental result in performance. We will explore this issue in more detail later in the course.</p> <p>One last thing, the <code><<-</code> assignment operator lets you break this rule. <strong>DONT USE IT</strong> (unless you really need to, and in that case, you should really think again about your function design to make sure you actually need to).</p> <pre class="r"><code>x <- 2 g <- function(x) { x <<- 6 x } g(x)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 6</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code>x</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 6</code></pre> <div id="lists-vs.vectors" class="section level3"> <h3>Lists vs.vectors</h3> <p>We saw that vectors are arrays of values, all of the same <em>class</em>. R also allows arrays of values that have different <em>class</em> or datatype. These are called <em>lists</em>. Here is a list containing a string, and a couple of numbers:</p> <pre class="r"><code>my_list <- list("Hector", 40, 71) my_list</code></pre> <pre><code>## [[1]] ## [1] "Hector" ## ## [[2]] ## [1] 40 ## ## [[3]] ## [1] 71</code></pre> <p>Indexing in lists uses different syntax from the indexing we saw before. To index an element in a list we would use a double-bracket <code>[[</code>.</p> <pre class="r"><code>my_list[[1]]</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "Hector"</code></pre> <p>In contrast, the single bracket <code>[</code> indexes a <em>part</em> of the list, and thus returns another list.</p> <pre class="r"><code>my_list[1]</code></pre> <pre><code>## [[1]] ## [1] "Hector"</code></pre> <p>That way we can use slice notation and other operations we saw when indexing vectors as before, but we get lists as results.</p> <pre class="r"><code>my_list[1:2]</code></pre> <pre><code>## [[1]] ## [1] "Hector" ## ## [[2]] ## [1] 40</code></pre> <p>List elements can have names as well:</p> <pre class="r"><code>named_list <- list(person="Hector", age=40, height=71) named_list</code></pre> <pre><code>## $person ## [1] "Hector" ## ## $age ## [1] 40 ## ## $height ## [1] 71</code></pre> <p>Which we can use to index elements as well (both with <code>[[</code> and <code>$</code>)</p> <pre class="r"><code>named_list[["person"]]</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "Hector"</code></pre> <pre class="r"><code>named_list$person</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] "Hector"</code></pre> <p>Lists can hold arbitrary objects as elements. For example you can have a vector of strings as an element in a list</p> <pre class="r"><code>my_list <- list(person=c("Hector", "Ringo", "Paul", "John"), 40, 71) my_list</code></pre> <pre><code>## $person ## [1] "Hector" "Ringo" "Paul" "John" ## ## [[2]] ## [1] 40 ## ## [[3]] ## [1] 71</code></pre> <p>Now, we come to a momentous occassion in understanding R. <code>data.frame</code>s are special instances of <em>lists</em>! But, in this case, every element in the list is a vector, and all vectors have exactly the same length. So <code>arrest_tab$age</code> indexes the named element <code>age</code> in the list <code>arrest_tab</code>!</p> <p>The pattern of <em>applying</em> functions to entries in vectors also holds for elements in lists. So, if we want to calculate smallest value for every attribute in our dataset, we could do something like this:</p> <pre class="r"><code>sapply(arrest_tab, function(v) sort(v)[1])</code></pre> <pre><code>## arrest age race ## "11126858" "0" "" ## sex arrestDate arrestTime ## "1" "01/01/2011" "00:00" ## arrestLocation incidentOffense incidentLocation ## "" "102-Questional Death" "" ## charge chargeDescription district ## "" "" "" ## post neighborhood Location.1 ## "111" "" ""</code></pre> </div> </div> <div id="matrices" class="section level2"> <h2>Matrices</h2> <p>The last important data structure Ill talk about in this introduction are matrices. One way of thinking about them is as <em>rectangular</em> data structures - they have two dimensions, rows and columns, like data tables - but only holds values of a single <em>class</em> or data type.</p> <pre class="r"><code>my_mat <- matrix(1:20, nrow=4, ncol=5) my_mat</code></pre> <pre><code>## [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5] ## [1,] 1 5 9 13 17 ## [2,] 2 6 10 14 18 ## [3,] 3 7 11 15 19 ## [4,] 4 8 12 16 20</code></pre> <p>These are important data structures in Machine Learning and statistics since most of the learning and analysis algorithms we will learn about assume that you can represent data as a matrix. Also, storage for these data structures is much more compact than data tables and lists. Since all elements are of the same <em>class</em> or type, language designers can be much smarter about how to lay out this data in memory.</p> </div>

<h1 class="title toc-ignore">A short note about pipes</h1> <h4 class="author"><em>CMSC320</em></h4> <h4 class="date"><em>2016-09-12</em></h4>
</div>
<div id="getting-started" class="section level2"> <h2>Getting started</h2> <p>Lets load the same data we used in the previous lab (look there for instructions on how to download).</p> <pre class="r"><code>arrest_tab <- read.csv("BPD_Arrests.csv", stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
# remember there's a naming issue in this dataset we need to fix colnames(arrest_tab)[3:4] <- c("race", "sex")
arrest_tab$race <- factor(arrest_tab$race) arrest_tab$sex <- factor(arrest_tab$sex) arrest_tab$incidentOffense <- factor(arrest_tab$incidentOffense)</code></pre> </div> <div id="making-the-process-explicit-with-pipes" class="section level2"> <h2>Making the process explicit with pipes</h2> <p>Weve discussed the idea of thinking about data analysis work in terms of pipelines, where we start from data of a certain shape (e.g., a <code>data.frame</code>) and apply transformations (functions) to obtain data that contains the computation we want. Consider the following example seen in class:</p> <p><em>What is the mean age of males arrested in the SOUTHERN district?</em></p> <p>We can frame the answer to this question as a series of data transformations to get the answer we are looking for:</p> <pre class="r"><code># filter data to observations we need index_vector <- arrest_tab$sex == "M" & arrest_tab$district == "SOUTHERN" tmp <- arrest_tab[index_vector,]
# select the attribute/column we need tmp <-tmp[,"age"]
# compute statistic required mean(tmp)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 32.28481</code></pre> <p>Lets rewrite this using functions to illustrate the point</p> <pre class="r"><code>filter_data <- function(data) { index_vector <- data$sex == "M" & data$district == "SOUTHERN" data[index_vector,] }
select_column <- function(data, column) { data[, column] }
tmp <- filter_data(arrest_tab) tmp <- select_column(tmp, "age") mean(tmp)</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 32.28481</code></pre> <p>So, this pattern of <em>data transform> data</em> becomes clearer when written that way.</p> <p>The <code>magrittr</code> package introduces <em>syntactic sugar</em> to make this explicit. We can write the above snippet using the pipe operator <code>%>%</code>:</p> <pre class="r"><code>library(magrittr)
arrest_tab %>% filter_data() %>% select_column("age") %>% mean()</code></pre> <pre><code>## [1] 32.28481</code></pre> <p>The <code>%>%</code> binary operator takes the value to its <strong>left</strong> and inserts it as the first argument of the function call to its <strong>right</strong>. So the expression <code>LHS %>% f(another_argument)</code> is <strong>equivalent</strong> to the expression <code>f(LHS, another_argument)</code>. We will see this pattern extensively in class because it explicitly presents the way we want to organize many of our data analysis tasks.</p> </div>
